2- Application Design Flaws:
              In this room, we focus on the OWASP Top 10:2025 categories that arise from mistakes in architecture and
              system design. You won’t just learn the theory — you’ll get hands-on practice through challenges that reinforceeach concept.


The categories we’ll cover are:
          • AS02 – Security Misconfigurations: 
                          Mistakes or oversights in how your systems, servers, or applications are set up.
          • AS03 – Software Supply Chain Failures: 
                          Risks introduced by third-party components, libraries, or dependencies.
          • AS04 – Cryptographic Failures: 
                          Weak or incorrect use of encryption that puts data at risk.
          • AS06 – Insecure Design: 
                          Flaws in the application’s overall design that make it inherently vulnerable.


Task 2-AS02: Security Misconfigurations:
                  Security misconfigurations happen when systems, servers, or applications are deployed with unsafe defaults,
                  incomplete settings, or exposed services. They are setup and architecture mistakes, not code bugs, that can create
                  easy entry points for attackers. Misconfigurations can occur in server settings, cloud resources, APIs, containers,
                  or AI/ML endpoints. They often result from lack of hardening, incomplete security reviews, outdated
                  components, or improper network segmentation. Even small mistakes can expose sensitive data, allow privilege
                  escalation, or compromise entire systems.
Common Patterns
          • Default credentials or weak passwords
          • Exposed services, APIs, or endpoints
          • Misconfigured cloud storage or permissions
          • Verbose error messages revealing system info
          • Outdated software or components Prevention
          • Harden default configurations and remove unused features
          • Enforce strong authentication and least privilege
          • Limit network exposure and segment sensitive resources
          • Keep software, frameworks, and containers up to  date
          • Hide stack traces and system information
          • Regularly audit configurations and secure AI endpoints

