Task 3-AS03: Software Supply Chain Failures:

              Software supply chain failures happen when applications depend on third-party components, libraries, services, or
AI models that are compromised, outdated, or improperly verified. These weaknesses are outside your own code, but
attackers can exploit them to inject malicious code, bypass security controls, leak sensitive data, or create backdoors.
Modern applications rely heavily on external packages, APIs, and AI models, making supply chain attacks
particularly dangerous. Such attacks can be automated, distributed, and hard to detect, affecting thousands of
systems at once.

Common Patterns
        • Using unverified or outdated libraries or dependencies
        • Automatic updates without verification
        • Over-reliance on third-party AI models
        • Insecure CI/CD pipelines or build processes
        • Poor tracking of licenses or component provenance Prevention
        • Verify all third-party components, libraries, and AI models before use
        • Monitor and patch dependencies regularly
        • Sign, audit, and verify software updates and packages
        • Lock down CI/CD pipelines and build processes
        • Include supply chain threat modeling in SDLC and deployment workflows


Task 4-AS04: Cryptographic Failures:

                  Cryptographic failures occur when encryption is used incorrectly, weakly, or not at all. This includes deprecated
algorithms, hard-coded keys, poor key management, or unencrypted sensitive data. Web applications rely on
cryptography to protect network traffic, secure stored data, verify identities, and safeguard secrets. When these
controls fail, attackers can steal passwords, tokens, or personal information, perform man-in-the-middle attacks,
brute-force weak keys, or simply access secrets that were never properly protected. This applies to traditional
systems as well as AI/ML models, where sensitive parameters or inputs can be exposed.
Common Patterns:
            • Using weak or deprecated algorithms (e.g., MD5,
            SHA-1, ECB mode)
            • Hard-coded secrets in code or config
            • Poor key rotation or management
            • Lack of encryption for sensitive data at rest or in
            transit
            • Self-signed or invalid TLS certificates
            • Exposing secrets in AI/ML systems 

Prevention:
            • Use strong, modern algorithms like AES-GCM, ChaCha20-Poly1305, and enforce TLS 1.3 with valid
            certificates
            • Use secure key management systems (e.g., AWS KMS, Azure Key Vault, HashiCorp Vault)
            • Rotate secrets and keys regularly following defined cryptoperiods
            • Maintain policies and SOPs for key lifecycle management
            • Keep an inventory of certificates, keys, and owners
            • Ensure AI/ML models never expose unencrypted secrets or sensitive inputs
Task 5-AS06: Insecure Design:

              Insecure design occurs when flawed logic or architecture is built into a system from the start. Causes include skipped
threat modeling, missing design reviews, or incorrect assumptions. AI systems add risk, as developers may
blindly trust models that generate queries, code, or classify users, embedding vulnerabilities into the system itself.
Example: Early Clubhouse assumed mobile-only access, but the backend API had no authentication, exposing
private user data.
Common Patterns
        • Weak business logic controls (e.g., approval or
        recovery flows)
        • AI components with unchecked authority or access
        • Test/debug bypasses left in production
        • No consistent threat or abuse-case review
Prevention
          • Treat all models as untrusted until verified
          • Validate and filter model inputs/outputs
          • Require human review for high-risk AI actions
          • Apply least privilege for users, APIs, and services
          • Ensure proper authentication, authorization, and
          session management
          • Continuously monitor and test the system for logic
          flaws, abuse paths, and emergent risks

